President Ivanov has said that he is not going to vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubts as to whether the minimum participation of 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid will be achieved.
The question of the elections in the referendum is as follows: "Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claims that it is worth changing if it makes Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia was divided, can join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the outcome in order for it to be considered decisive.
The change of name requires a majority of two thirds of Parliament.
According to the election commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1:00 p.m.
However, participation was only 16 per cent, compared with 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 per cent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital of Skopje.
Prime Minister of Macedonia Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko vote in the referendum in Macedonia on the change of name, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the Parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organized a small stage and place out chairs in front of the tents set up by the boycotters of the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneaking in through the back door," said Kavardarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership of NATO would lead to much-needed investments in Macedonia, with over 20% unemployment.
"I think that the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80% of our citizens are for the EU and NATO," said Zaev when he voted.
He said that a "Yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Surveys, between 30 and 43 percent of voters thought to vote in the referendum, which falls under the minimum participation required.
According to another study conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 percent of participants thought to vote on Sunday.
