John Edward: Language skills crucial for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain outstanding academic results and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, which are supported only by individual and collective advances in sport, art, music and other social engagements.
With up to 30 000 pupils in Scotland, schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement adapted curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desired subjects at schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we can not only rely on English when we create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received A in the final sample Higher Grade.
Data collected from SCIS 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students who studied Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Language as a topic choice is now considered as important as natural knowledge, technology, engineering and mathematics at curriculum level in independent schools and beyond.
A study carried out by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills 2014 concluded that employers for various reasons had difficulty filling their vacancies, with 17 per cent attributed to a lack of skills in languages.
With this said, language skills become all the more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills become necessary in a globalised world.
Regardless of career choices, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries, automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adult Britishs published by YouGov 2013, 75 per cent responded that they could not speak a foreign language well enough to keep a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that came up in total in a two-digit percentage (15 per cent).
Therefore, it is so important to invest in language teaching for our children.
To be able to speak several languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance to find meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach in languages considered to be the most important for the UK by 2020, for example Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and get them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly language that continues to be crucial for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication capacity".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
Il faut bien le fiaire.
John Edward, Head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
