Harvard students take courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has led all doctoral students to improve their sleep habits in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture to study through caffeine-filled "deepings".
An academic study found that students at the world's leading universities are often unconscious about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first in his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the effect of sleep failure on learning.
"At the end of that, a girl came up to me and said, "Why can't I know this until now, in my last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organized for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, and improves their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the University's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that the students suffered from severe sleep shortages during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In part of the course there is a picture of a student room, where the students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athetic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep failure can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campuses, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change the students' behavior right away.
But we think they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "deep" still exists, he says and added that modern technology and constantly increasing pressure on the students meant that sleep lack was a growing problem.
To ensure that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in a state of hunger and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course and has read one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course was an eye opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study programme before they start their studies at the high-performance institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that the students consider setting an alarm for when to lie down and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" issued by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn around in the day, leading to sleep problems.
