The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the South and Dwarve Pippistrell as well as brown lending and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special players will be placed in important places around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area image of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation advisor, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for the bat and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest fields for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has decreased considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by building and development work that affects farmland and the loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as attacks from hu tax.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organisation has ten trained experts who regularly carry out investigations, inspects bon and sometimes conduct rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threeave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home for eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager David Thompson says that the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here on Threeave we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of wheat trees and a variety of favorable habitats.
But there is much about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before carrying out maintenance in real estate, since it is possible that accidental destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young people, and possibly eradicate an entire population.
The bats are peaceful and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or destroy their nest.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are doing."
