Algal flower: The levels decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from Florida's Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in algal bloom concentrations for parts of the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, olive flowers are reported in the areas around the large municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which may indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The algal flower extends along over 20 miles of the coast, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee.
Flies can be seen about a mile and a half out of the sea outside the large municipality of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algal flowering has also been observed in the large municipality of Pasco.
Medium concentrations within or off the coast of Pinellas have been reported during the past week. Outside the coast of Hillsborough low to high concentrations, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manatee, background concentrations to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota, background concentrations to medium concentrations on or off the coast of Lee, and low concentrations in Collier.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come from the large municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in northwestern Florida that past week.
